{"tid":43381,"cid":5,"subCid":0,"title":"[炸鳩支那] Nukemap 核彈地圖","createTime":"2016-12-17T12:45:22.000Z","updateTime":"2016-12-17T13:28:58.000Z","uid":9348,"like":2,"dislike":0,"uniUserReply":0,"replies":[{"pid":"bc1bab41bf6775c515151fb82e883e3f278a024e","tid":43381,"uid":9348,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2016-12-17T12:45:22.000Z","msg":"This map shows what would happen to you if a nuclear bomb was dropped where you live<br />\n<br />\nPosted about 3 hours ago by Jessica Brown in offbeat<br />\n<br />\nIn what seems like an increasingly hostile world, where North Korea has stepped up its nuclear weapons testing and Russia&rsquo;s relations with the West continue to deteriorate, it&rsquo;s important to make light of the situation so we don&rsquo;t spend all day screaming.<br />\n<br />\nAnd in that vein, the internet can&rsquo;t get enough of the tool that tells you what would happen if a nuclear bomb hit different cities across the world.<br />\n<br />\nThe tool 'Nukemap' measures the effects of nuclear bomb strikes with various sizes of payload. It was created by Alex Wellerstein, a nuclear historian at the Stevens Institute of Technology.<br />\n<br />\n<a href=\"http://nuclearsecrecy.com/nukemap/\" data-sr-url=\"https://r.lihkg.com/link?u=http%3A%2F%2Fnuclearsecrecy.com%2Fnukemap%2F&d=sU61sAx2fcf5rzR%2Bp6lq8ZkBtgkcD0hE3Em2wkgk6m8%3D&h=497f1321\" target=\"_blank\">http://nuclearsecrecy.com/nukemap/</a>"},{"pid":"b923590706231e2bc902281569e7041ed08f4c0f","tid":43381,"uid":9348,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2016-12-17T12:48:09.000Z","msg":"<img src=\"https://na.cx/i/43p7L2e.jpg\" data-thumbnail-src=\"https://i.lih.kg/thumbnail?u=https%3A%2F%2Fna.cx%2Fi%2F43p7L2e.jpg&h=64268058&s={SIZE}\" /><br />\nTsar Bomba <img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/agree.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /> <img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/agree.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /> <img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/agree.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" />"},{"pid":"b059ccd